children.name: Text Description
children.characters: Radio buttons when you want to allow users to select a single option

children.name: Text Description
children.characters:
A Radio Group is a form element that lets users select a 
single choice from a list of at least two options.

children.name: Text
children.characters:
Radio groups are used when a user has a single choice to make from two or more options. The user can only choose one radio selection at a time.

Radio groups should:

Include at least two or more options.
Allow users to select only one option.

children.name: Text
children.characters: You can stack Radios horizontally or vertically - Spacing should be 16px between each option.

children.name: Text
children.characters: Depending on your use case, choose from one of the variant states

children.name: Text
children.characters: The focus state we use for this component is not currently available to use in Prism as a variable. But it is documented here and can be viewed in storybook.

children.name: Text
children.characters:
A user can tab through a Radio and select an item by clicking the enter key.
an outline will show around the current tabbed into element.
If a radio is on its own, an outline will show around the single radio - It its also paired with label text, the outline will show around the group.

children.name: Radios and Radio Button Groups Design Patterns

Radios are used when only one choice may be selected in a series of options. Radio button groups provide an option for: When you have a simple either / or option to present Providing some visual hierarchy to radio selection groups Icons are appropriate for selection
